{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"833350b8-80ea-4a56-b974-c4d9dc14deb1","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports when a process crashes. NativeAOT apps don't include `createdump`, but you can find the macOS-generated crash report here:\n\n**Crash reports (`.ips` files):**\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\nYou can also open **Console.app** → **Crash Reports** in the sidebar to browse them.\n\n**To enable core dumps** (disabled by default on macOS):\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nThen re-run your app — the core dump appears in `/cores/`.\n\n> 💡 Once you have the `.ips` file, the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill can help you symbolicate the native frames back to .NET runtime source lines. Just say the word if you'd like to symbolicate it.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0dd09cb3-505c-4f1e-90d9-a41c3987c8be","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a diagnostic question - let me check if any of my available skills are relevant.\n\nThe `dump-collect` skill is about configuring and collecting crash dumps for modern .NET applications, and it covers NativeAOT. Let me invoke it.\n\nActually, looking more carefully: the `dump-collect` skill says \"Configure and collect crash dumps for modern .NET applications. USE FOR: enabling automatic crash dumps for CoreCLR or NativeAOT...\" - this seems relevant.\n\nBut wait, the user is asking about finding an *existing* crash report on macOS after a crash already happened, not about setting up dump collection. \n\nI should also consider the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill - it handles symbolication of .NET runtime frames in Apple platform crash logs, including macOS. That could be useful for understanding the crash report once found. The `dump-collect` skill is still relevant for NativeAOT scenarios, though it's more about proactive setup. I think `apple-crash-symbolication` is probably the better fit here since the user needs help locating and interpreting an existing crash report on macOS. On macOS, since NativeAOT doesn't include the managed crash dump infrastructure, the system generates its own crash reports stored in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` or accessible through Console.app. Core dumps can be enabled with `ulimit -c unlimited`, though macOS disables them by default and requires SIP adjustments to fully enable.","outputTokens":931,"requestId":"2C5F:C87BE:284CB85:2CCD753:69F94C86"},"id":"f7087189-ccd0-4754-809a-d941e2bb432c","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:49:17.702Z","parentId":"9c8fdf61-269a-44e8-916a-497d43c8efe6"}
